It contains all the elemens required to interact with the user
This group contains the roles which the user expects his agents to play
An assistant represents the user in the system.

A user assistant delegates on a buyer to obtain cinema tickets satisfiying some requirements. Therefore, a buyer is responsible for locating a cinema selling tickets under conditions that match the user assistant requirements.

A cinema offers tickets for the movies it shows. Each cinema has its own characteristics, different movies, sessions and so on. The cinema performs the show and, after it finishes, it removes any locks from current seats, so that they can be reserved again.

The agent moves from a PDA enviroment to another environment where the transaction is executed
Buyer moves to the node where the seller is
This mental state is reusable for all buyers

The assistant informs the buyer that a new cinema ticket is needed. The assistant informs the buyer on the preferences. The preferences cover the preferred seats, preferred price, preferred sessions, and preferred add-ons (nachos and so on). The user is informed of the success or the failure of the query.
There is failure if none of the cinemas had tickets satisfying the requirements. Then, the assistant is free to relax the constaints or give up.

A buyer contacts a seller in order to get a ticket. The buyer asks the cinemas about the attributes of the service, i.e., about the number of available sessions, available seats, price, and extras. The cinema offers as well a price for the ticket. The conditions can match those of the assistant, so the buyer accepts and starts a transaction to deliver the money. When money is received, the cinema delivers the ticket.
If the user assistant preferences are not met. Then the buyer informs the cinema that there is no further interest in the proposal, and proceeds to locate another cinema. If no more are available, then, the ticket sell is considered as a failure.

The relationship between the assistant and the buyer is dinamic. Initially, an assistant does not know with which buyer is going to interact. Hence, a first step consists in asking the different buyers if they would like to act as a representative to cinemas.

Each buyer can represent only one assistant. There are no specific means to determine which buyer is better, at least in this version. Also, there are no mechanisms for the buyer to decide whether if it is profitable to accept or not the association proposal.

The system intends to provide a ticket selling service where a user representative can contact each cinema and proceed with the transaction. The case study considers a user connecting to the system and instructing a representative (User assistant) to obtain a cinema ticket. The assistant contacts another representative (buyer) so that this representative obtains the ticket. The representative contacts different cinemas representatives (seller) until an adequate cinema is located (adequate means there are free seats and the price is good enough). Once obtained, the ticket is delivered, through the different representatives, to the user.

This functionality is comprised into three use cases: locate an assistant, buy cinema ticket and sell a ticket. The first use case captures the functionality for associating a user assistant with a buyer. The second use case represents the act of contacting the first representative (user assistant) to delegate the responsiblity of locating and obtaining the ticket to a second representative (buyer). The third use case represents the individual contact with cinema representatives to negotiate the sale.

The workflow starts with the selection of a movie to watch. This movie is determined perhaps according to some useer preferences or by a direct request from the user.

It continues with the selection of a cinema to consult. This query selects a cinema using a yellow pages service.

Then the cinema determines the availability (seats and price) and generates an offer. This offer is send to the representative.

The offer is considered and, depending on the conditions (seats and price), two alternatives are considered: either looking for another cinema or accepting the offer obtained from the current cinema representative.

If the offer is not accepted, another cinema is considered. The selection criteria is the same as the initial one (task choose cinema).

If the offer is accepted, the representative proceeds to pay the cinema representative.

The payment is gathered by the cinema and processed. In return, it generates an electronic ticket.

This ticket is supplied later on to the original user representative.

node.id: User wants to watch a movie

mapproperties.key:
This diagram synthetizes all the tasks involved in the collaboration between the "user representative", the seller, and the buyer. Each task has associated a goal being satisfied, a responsible (usually a role), required helper applications, and identifies its inputs/outputs.

Some of these taks start interactions. In this case, there are exactly three: Choose movie, choose cinema, and Choose movie. The task "choose movie" is activated when the user requests, through some GUI, watching a movie (event "user wants to watch a movie"). The user is not requesting a specific movie, hence that the task is supposed to determine the movie, perhaps by means of inspection of user preferences. The result of this task is a request to find tickets for a movie, the name of the movie, and an interaction to obtain the ticket. Tasks "look for another" and "choose cinema" are similar since both initiate interaction with cinema representatives. The task "choose cinema" receives the request of finding a cinema shooting the desired movie. To find available cinemas, the task uses a directory. From this list of cinemas, the task chooses one and initiates an interaction in order to negotiate with the cinema. The task "look for another" is activated when the task "process offer" produces a "not interested" fact. This task produces a "buy ticket" interaction and chooses new actors to participate into it. The task is triggered when an offer generated by a cinema is not satisfying the criteria (having enough seats and a price within a concrete range). In principle, this task would choose other cinemas available. It is assumed that at least one of the existing cinemas will be able to provide the desired ticket.

The rest of tasks are dedicated to intermediate processing. The "determine availability" task receives the request from the user assistant and generates an offer for the movie. The "process offer" task consumes the offer and produces either a "pay the money" or a "not interested" fact. The first fact means that the offer is accepted and the second fact means it was not. If the fact "pay the money" is generated, the task "pay ticket" is activated and produces a transaction identifier which is passed to the task "get money", responsiblity of the seller. The task "get money" produces the ticket, which is transferred to the buyer by means of the interaction where this task is allocated. The ticket together with the transaction payment is used to activate the task "process ticket". This task is responsiblity of the buyer and will be activated after the task "get money" is executed on the seller side (otherwiser the fact "ticket" would not exist). The ticket is passed to the user assistant, which consumes the ticket information and other related information handled in the request. Besides, this task presents the ticket to the user.

Each task produces additional information in each agent. This information is required to connect each task with the next ones and perform intermediate computations. Hence, after each agent finishes its part in the collaboration, is responsible of cleaning the information no longer needed. This is the purpose of all tasks pursuing the goal "clean mental state".

This is the protocol regulating the interaction between the user assistant and the buyer. In the protocol, the user assistant requests the buyer to obtain a ticked for a movie. To do so, the movie and the request is sent. The information sent is processed initially by the task choose cinema. This task will later trigger others responsible of further processing. After the buyer obtains the electronic ticket, it delivers the ticket to the user assistant. The assistant process the ticket with the task "Process ticket obtained".

The diagram indicates as well that the act of requesting the ticket happens before the act of giving the ticket.

The user assistant and the buyer colaborates according to the protocol established in "asking for a ticket". This interaction pursues two main goals: assist the user and sell tickets. The protocol dictating how the interaction happens is represented by the entity "GRASIA buy description".

This diagram represents the collaboration between a buyer and a seller. The interaction pursues the implementation of the sales process between a cinema and a user representative. The user representative is the buyer, and the cinema representative is the seller. The protocol that governs the interaction is represented by the entity GRASIA find cinema interaction description.

This diagram introduces the protocol followed when a buyer wants to obtain a ticket from a selller. The order of the messages sent appears at the bottom of the diagram. First, the buyer informs the seller what movie is interested into. The seller initiates a task "determine availability" to process the request and determine the price and available seats. The answer is sent with interaction unit "ticket exists" in form of an offer. The offer is processed on the buyer side with task "process offer". The result of the process is a decision about whether to accept the offer or to reject it.

In the first case, the interaction unit "I want it" is initiated. As a consequence, a task "pay ticket" is executed, producing a payment identifier. The seller receives the payment identifier and proceeds to verify if the payment has been received already. After checking this, the ticket is produced and delivered to the buyer with interaction unit "sell ticket".

In the second case, the interactino unit "I do not want it" is started. The result for the buyer is that another cinema is located and an interaction protocol like this one is tried again. For the seller, this implicates cleaning the data referring to this transaction.

mapproperties.key:
In the system, four agents are defined playing the roles user assistant, buyer and seller. The "Interface agent" plays the "user assistant" role and pursues to assist the user in obtaining a cinema ticket and finding the proper cinemas. The "buyer agent" plays the role "buyer" and has the responsibility of interacting with the cinemas in order to obtain the tickets. Its goals are assisting the user as well, obtaining the ticket from providers, and finding the proper cinemas. The "seller agent1" and "seller agent2" play the seller role. Both correspond to two hypothetical different implementations of the cinema representativeness functionality. A seller pursues to sell tickets, mainly.

Each agent has a clean mental state goal. This goal refers to the need of restoring the mental state of each agent to the conditions where the agent can provide the service again. Each service provision implies the generation of temporal data. This data has to be cleaned after finishing the service provision.

Each agent has a number of applications, developed externally, that provide basic functionality not related with agent concerns. Also, these applications are used to connect with the environment and obtain information from it. These applications are used by the different tasks each agent has.

The UserGUI application represents the GUI the user interacts with. This application produces events as a result of the actions of the user. These events trigger different actions on the agent. In this case, the event considered is "user wants to watch a movie" and the action triggered on the interface agent, which plays the user assistant role, is "choose movie". This application has some methods that permit to interact with the user, concretely, the deliver of the ticket to the user.

The Virtual terminal application represents a payment gateway with methods able to deliver electronically the money to a concrete recipient. This is used to send the money to the cinema.

The cinema directory represents a white pages service specialized in cinemas. Therefore, it contains all existing cinemas.
